\begin_layout Subsection*

\lang english
3.
 Roles and Responsibilities
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
IT Director.
 The IT Director serves as Incident Commander by default,
 as established in 
\series bold
Policy 4.01
\series default
,
 and exercises Designated Appointment and Emergency Declaration Authority per 
\series bold
Policy 1.08
\series default
.
 During the containment phase,
 the IT Director completes catch-up Change Control Authority (CCA) review for all Emergency changes within 24 hours of implementation per 
\series bold
Policy 3.09
\series default
,
 and approves any exceptions to this policy per 
\series bold
Policy 1.08
\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Assistant IT Director.
 The Assistant IT Director serves as Incident Commander in the IT Director's absence or by designation.
 The Assistant IT Director owns playbook maintenance under standing authority,
 ensures catch-up RFC documentation and CCA review timelines are met,
 and ensures that affected CI records are flagged at the time of containment action for subsequent update per 
\series bold
Policy 3.08
\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
IT Department Personnel.
 IT Department personnel execute containment directives under Incident Commander authority.
 Personnel shall not take any containment action without an associated Redmine work order and IC authorization.
 Personnel shall document all actions in work order Notes in real time,
 or as close to real time as operational conditions permit,
 consistent with the documentation standards established in 
\series bold
Policy 4.02
\series default
 Section 6.4.
 Personnel shall not destroy,
 overwrite,
 or cause the disposition of audit logs under any circumstances during the containment phase.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Network Administrator.
 The Network Administrator leads network-related containment actions as directed by the Incident Commander,
 flags affected CI records at the time of containment action for subsequent update,
 and creates catch-up RFC documentation within the 24-hour window established by 
\series bold
Policy 3.09
\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Systems Administrator.
 The Systems Administrator leads server- and endpoint-related containment actions as directed by the Incident Commander,
 flags affected CI records at the time of containment action for subsequent update,
 and creates catch-up RFC documentation within the 24-hour window established by 
\series bold
Policy 3.09
\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Incident Commander (when not the IT Director).
 When the IC is not the IT Director,
 all IC authority is incorporative from 
\series bold
Policy 4.01
\series default
 and 
\series bold
Policy 1.08
\series default
.
 The specific IC authorities exercised under this policy are:
 containment mode selection,
 Emergency Change designation,
 containment-complete determination,
 primary category designation for multi-category incidents,
 and emergency procurement initiation per 
\series bold
Policy 1.08
\series default
.
\end_layout

